. I have been following this issue, and feel like adding my thoughts on this :)
I am pretty sure that the Html5Shiv needs to be loaded outside of Lab.JS. Consider this flow
1. Browser downloads the page
2. It applys the style
   - Browser runs into an HTML5 tag and doesn't know what it is...the tag is ignored
3. Lab chain runs and executes the HTML5 shiv
How would the browser know to style the HTML5 element without the shiv being loaded? You need to load the shiv BEFORE the lab chain runs to make the execution flow like
1. Browser downloads the page
2. Scripts are executed...Html5Shiv loaded 
3. It applys the style
   - Browser runs into an HTML5 tag and now knows what to do
4. Lab chain runs the rest of the JS
This is how I do it, and I don't really notice any performance impact. Essential scripts like the Html5Shiv just need to be loaded like this. If you have your server set up properly the shiv will be cached and the user won't have to download it with every request.  (or use a CDN). In fact, the Html5Shiv site even says

It must be included before the < body > element (i.e. in the < head >) 

Loading it via LAB.js just isn't going to work. Sorry :/
